utterances.text: i'm wedding planner and it's pride month
let's talk about gender neutral wedding terminology
so first up straight off the bat
i am a straight cis female (she/her)
so take that for what it's worth
but i am an lgbtq plus friendly professional wedding vendor
so i'm just sharing the knowledge that i have for my industry
if you have more to add that you wanna share please let me know
leave it in the comments
were always wanting to learn more right
okay so let's just talk about it
and of course if you like the terms bride groom husband and wife use them
i just wanna let you know there are alternatives
and you can choose whatever makes you feel safe and included and respected
so let's get into the list
i think being engaged is probably the most natural of all of the terminology
you could just say i am engaged
also fiance when spoken is gender neutral at its core (see also: feyoncé)
the written word fiancé does come from french roots
so it does have a male and a female version when written (fiancé/fiancée)
but if you were to just verbally saying my fiance and i are going on vacation
that in another self is gender neutral right
other options would be patrol that are nearly weds
pick what you like
whether you are dating or engaged or married
on the next category is just terms as a couple
um spouse i guess implies that you are married
but partners significant other beloved lovers companions
those are just some terms that just describe your your union
isn't it really cute to say
that's my beloved
okay words that are alternative to the term bride or groom
truthfully as a wedding planner
i would probably just call you by your name
like at rehearsal
if i was giving directions
i would just say okay
now sarah is gonna do this
or if there's a term that you prefer
i would just call you that
but if you looking for a little something
something to call yourself on the day of your wedding
just call yourself a vip
because you are the most important person in the room
you are the star of the show
honey so it is your wedding day
and i'll call you anything you want
not a serious note
wedding person is also a gender neutral term
okay wedding party
um the alternatives for like
bridesmaids or groomsmen
of course you can have anyone stand on either side of you
regardless of gender
so if you wanna have a best woman instead of a best man
or um a man of honor instead of a made of honor
that's great
but those aren't gender neutral
you can have a person of honor
or a best person
again another opportunity to use the term vips
say these are all of my vips
they are your entourage
they're your crew
are your backup dancers
a more formal term would be your attendance
because they are attending to you
some gender neutral terms for your little kiddos
would be ring person
flower person
flower pal are you
you little people
or you just call them like
the kiddo crew or something
okay so now let's talk about ceremony time
and you're looking for an alternative
to the phrase
i now pronounce you husband and wife
there's lots of options here
you could say
i now pronounce you partners in life
i now pronounce you companions for life
i now pronounce you married
and wedded bliss
i now pronounce you joined together
in wedding union
you could start with your first names
and say person a and person b
i now pronounce you married
you can inject a lot of personality into your wedding ceremony
you could say
i now pronounce you partners and crime
or if you have a connection to a favorite tv show
you could say
i now pronounce you each other's lobster
from friends
if you like the office
you could say
i now pronounce you soups
thanks i whatever you like
and for the kiss
you could say
you may now kiss your spouse
you may now kiss your partner
you may now kiss each other
you could say
you may now kiss

if you have more
